git init		   Initializes a new Git repository.
git clone <url>		   Creates a local copy of a remote repository.
git status		   Shows the working directory and staging area status.
git add <file>		   Adds a file to the staging area.
git commit -m "message"	   Commits staged changes with a message.
git push origin <branch>   Pushes commits to a remote branch.
git pull origin <branch>   Fetches and merges changes from a remote branch.
git branch <branch_name>   Create a new branch with the specified name.
git checkout <branch>	   Switches to a different branch.
git merge <branch>	   Merges changes from one branch into another.
git rebase <branch>	   Re-applies commits on top of another branch.
git log			   Shows commit history.
git log --oneline	   Show log in linear format
git diff		   Shows differences between commits, files, or the working directory.
git show <commit>	   Displays information about a specific commit.
git config	    	   Sets Git configuration options.
git reset <commit>	   Resets the current HEAD to a specific state.
git revert <commit>	   Reverses a specific commit.
git stash		   Temporarily saves changes to the working directory.
git tag	Creates, lists, or deletes tags.
git remote		   Manages remote repositories.
